explanation:
Area of region bounded by the curve $y=\cos x$ between $x=0$ and $x=\pi$ is shaded region.
<img src="https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1m7hmvnre/9db67d7a-585e-4aef-8148-6c72aa5b558e/b79206a0-f1e5-11ef-aab0-892656acd133/file-jaoe38c1m7hmvnrf.png?format=png" data-orsrc="https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1m7hmvnre/9db67d7a-585e-4aef-8148-6c72aa5b558e/b79206a0-f1e5-11ef-aab0-892656acd133/file-jaoe38c1m7hmvnrf.png" loading="lazy" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline" alt="KCET 2018 Mathematics - Area Under The Curves Question 5 English Explanation">
$$
\begin{aligned}
&amp;\text { Required area of shaded region }\\
&amp;\begin{aligned}
&amp; =\int_0^{\pi / 2} \cos x d x+\left|\int_{\pi / 2}^\pi \cos x d x\right| \\
&amp; =[\sin x]_0^{\pi / 2}+\left|[\sin x]_{\pi / 2}^\pi\right| \\
&amp; =\left[\sin \frac{\pi}{2}-\sin 0\right]+\left|\sin \pi-\sin \frac{\pi}{2}\right| \\
&amp; =(1-0)+|(0-1)| \\
&amp; =1+1=2 \text { sq units }
\end{aligned}
\end{aligned}
$$
